WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.000
The nice thing about learning bslib is it serves as a general foundation that not only

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:27.080
Shiny and R Markdown directly can use, but also extension packages like flex-dashboard

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:33.720
and package-down and book-down, like some of these other packages that fit in an ecosystem

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:41.000
and essentially like extend R Markdown or extend Shiny.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:48.400
Because of how we've sort of approached this problem, at least a handful of these packages

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:55.320
have pretty nice seamless integration with the ability to, like, if you have a theme

00:00:55.400 --> 00:01:01.480
that you're already using for your Shiny application, you can pretty easily sort of copy-paste that

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:07.320
over to a flex-dashboard app or your package-down website or something like that.

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:12.199
If you're using bslib, make sure you have a more recent version of Shiny and R Markdown

00:01:12.199 --> 00:01:15.959
when you're using it.

00:01:15.959 --> 00:01:23.800
And the real straightforward basic usage is to take advantage of this theme argument.

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:31.720
If we're talking about Shiny, there's a few different ways to create sort of the page container.

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:38.040
So if you want that classic navbar-page look, you would start with navbar-page and give

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:43.080
the theme argument to this bs-theme object.

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:51.160
And with this bs-theme function, you can specify the bootstrap version that you want to use.

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:58.919
So I think still we're defaulting to bootstrap 4, but soon we will default to bootstrap 5.

00:01:58.919 --> 00:02:06.120
But if you want your project to be fully reproducible, we do recommend, like, fully specifying the

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:11.399
version so that if we change the default in the future, you won't be surprised that you're

00:02:11.399 --> 00:02:16.080
getting a new bootstrap version.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:23.199
So this is kind of like the easiest way to opt in to a new bootstrap version is to call

00:02:23.199 --> 00:02:31.919
this bs-theme function, give it a version, and pass it to the theme argument of a page layout.

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:37.039
And the equivalent way of doing something like this in R Markdown is to work with the

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:41.839
theme arguments of a output format.

00:02:41.839 --> 00:02:46.800
So not all output formats will have a theme argument.

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:53.600
This historically has just been used for output formats that are HTML-based.

00:02:53.600 --> 00:03:01.119
And theme has historically meant, like, choose a different boot swatch theme, essentially.

00:03:01.119 --> 00:03:09.600
So you might have used this and said something like theme darkly or theme cyborg or some

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:11.440
boot swatch theme.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:17.440
But we've now extended this interface, essentially, with bs-lib so that you can provide any collection

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:23.520
of arguments to this bs-theme function with all of your custom theming parameters.

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:32.000
And then, essentially, this HTML document will use all of those custom settings to influence

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:40.800
the CSS that goes on the page in the same way that would happen for the navbar page.

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:46.160
That's one of the great things about learning bs-lib once is you can use it in both of those

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:46.720
projects.

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:54.000
You just have to kind of work around the fact that this is YAML and not R code.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:00.720
So some of the things that you might be more easily done over here in the R side might

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:04.800
be a little bit trickier to convert that to pure YAML.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:11.679
If you have more recent versions of bs-lib and Flex Dashboard, bs-lib itself comes with

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:13.839
some different templates in RStudio.

00:04:15.279 --> 00:04:19.600
So I could show you how that looks.

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:31.040
If I go to file, new file in RStudio, and then go to R Markdown, this little window

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:31.920
will pop up.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:41.040
And then if you choose the from template option, bs-lib will provide a few different sort of

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:43.679
examples of how to get started with R Markdown.

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:50.799
And I believe, I don't know if I have the newest version of Flex Dashboard, but we also

00:04:50.799 --> 00:04:56.399
have some Flex Dashboard templates that show you how to use bs-lib with it.

00:04:56.640 --> 00:05:07.440
So if I just open that one, this will give me like a more worked out, complete theme.

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:13.200
And so it's not going to be super clear or super obvious.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:19.760
Like one unfortunate way about how this currently works, which we're looking to improve in the

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:29.839
future, is that I don't like, how am I going to remember what arguments go to this theme

00:05:29.839 --> 00:05:30.399
parameter?

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:38.559
You know, I'm using bg here, which represents the background color, fg, which represents

00:05:38.559 --> 00:05:44.799
the foreground color, a primary color, secondary, and a couple different font settings.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:54.239
And I guess the way that I keep track of this, and I'm hoping other people will remember

00:05:54.239 --> 00:06:06.399
this as well, is you can pass in any argument to this bs-theme function to this theme YAML

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:07.359
setting over here.

00:06:07.519 --> 00:06:13.600
So as you can see, the first few listed are the bg, as I said, a color string for the

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:17.040
background, fg, color string for the foreground.

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:20.959
There's a handful of different like accent color settings.

00:06:23.119 --> 00:06:28.000
So primary is going to be, you know, the most obvious one that changes the most colors,

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:34.720
but then it's also possible to control some other colors with these other accents.

00:06:35.279 --> 00:06:38.880
Control some other colors with these other accent color settings.

00:06:40.079 --> 00:06:44.000
There's three different main settings for fonts.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.119
So the base font is going to be kind of like the global font setting for everything on

00:06:49.119 --> 00:06:49.679
the page.

00:06:50.559 --> 00:06:58.079
Code will target, you know, like code blocks, essentially, headings for things like titles.

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:04.399
And then you can also do some things like scale the fonts to larger sizes.

00:07:05.679 --> 00:07:16.239
And eventually we'll get through, talk about like the fact that there's actually hundreds

00:07:16.239 --> 00:07:24.320
of different theming controls that you have access to via bs-theme, but they're not all

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:25.519
named arguments.

00:07:25.519 --> 00:07:32.959
And we've kind of intentionally designed things that way, where we want to allow you

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:38.480
to set any of these sort of main color and font settings and have it work across the

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:40.799
board on all Bootstrap versions.

00:07:42.799 --> 00:07:48.640
But then when you get more targeted and, you know, set a more specific style on a very

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:59.200
particular thing on a website, we want to make it a little bit harder to discover those

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:05.519
things and make you aware of the fact that this could potentially break with a newer

00:08:05.519 --> 00:08:09.519
version of Bootstrap and we're not like committing to supporting this across the board.

00:08:12.799 --> 00:08:16.799
So let me actually just show you a real example of what's going on here.

00:08:19.200 --> 00:08:22.160
So let me just knit this.

00:08:22.799 --> 00:08:23.279
All right.

00:08:23.279 --> 00:08:28.399
So this is the template or the result of that template.

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:36.080
So that main BG setting is going in and determining like this background color here,

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:43.919
the foreground color, I believe, will be used for these text colors here.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:51.039
And the thing about, you know, implementing a dark theme like this that you might want

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:58.400
to keep in mind is, you know, there's actually at least tens, if not hundreds, of actual

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:03.119
color styles that are going into the end result on the page.

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:11.599
So, for example, like the gray on this background for this code block is actually like a mixture

00:09:11.599 --> 00:09:15.919
between the background and the foreground color that you're choosing.

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:17.039
That you're choosing.

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:24.159
So when you give us those two main settings, you want it to be kind of a high contrast

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:30.799
difference between probably two like grayscale colors.

00:09:32.479 --> 00:09:40.799
So that's why, you know, I kind of recommend, you know, first of all, it's primarily most

00:09:40.799 --> 00:09:45.200
useful for just implementing a dark theme like this, where you just set the background

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:49.119
to something that's close to black and foreground that's something close to white.

00:09:50.159 --> 00:09:52.559
Then you can easily have a dark theme here.

00:09:53.919 --> 00:10:00.479
But I think people quickly want to like set like colors with different hues, like a green

00:10:00.479 --> 00:10:02.400
for a background or something like that.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:07.359
And just be careful, like if you want to do something like that, you want to set a dark

00:10:07.359 --> 00:10:14.320
green, like choose a lighter green for the foreground color and don't choose like a light

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:20.960
red or something like that, because you'll get mixtures of those two colors to determine

00:10:20.960 --> 00:10:22.559
stuff like these code blocks.

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:38.400
Also, I've kind of already jumped one of the punch lines here where this template is also

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:43.359
showing you another package that could be kind of thought of as like a sister package

00:10:43.359 --> 00:10:57.119
to bslib called thematic, which essentially allows you to pretty easily translate on some

00:10:57.119 --> 00:11:05.119
level the CSS styles that are going onto the page and have those styles actually determine

00:11:05.119 --> 00:11:09.599
new global styling defaults for your R plots.

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:16.960
So, to make that happen, I just called thematic RMD, since this is an R markdown document,

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:27.039
thematic has a thematic RMD, where this extra setting will also make it so that it uses

00:11:27.039 --> 00:11:35.840
the font settings that I've set up here in this document as well to use that for the

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:38.080
fonts that are in the plot.

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:48.640
And the reason why this isn't really enabled by default is that, you know, chances are

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:53.760
you don't actually have the font installed in your R graphics device.

00:11:54.719 --> 00:12:01.520
So thematic will actually, in the case that it's detected that you don't have that font

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:10.479
installed, it will actually go out and grab fonts from Google's font API.

00:12:11.919 --> 00:12:19.919
So if you're not familiar, there's a fonts.google.com that provides you access to like hundreds,

00:12:19.919 --> 00:12:22.239
if not thousands of different free fonts.

00:12:22.559 --> 00:12:28.479
Essentially, we've tried to design both bslib and thematic in the sense of like, if you

00:12:28.479 --> 00:12:38.239
can find the font on this fonts.google.com, you don't have to do any other work beyond

00:12:38.239 --> 00:12:43.679
just specifying the font, and we'll do all the work of downloading and caching and making

00:12:43.679 --> 00:12:48.640
sure that that font is actually available when people try to view your website.

00:12:49.599 --> 00:12:53.119
So there's a lot of work to make that all that magic happen in the background, if you've

00:12:53.119 --> 00:12:54.880
ever worked with fonts before.

00:12:57.599 --> 00:13:04.640
And I kind of glossed over the fact that there is kind of a special way to use Google fonts

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:05.840
with bslib.

00:13:07.039 --> 00:13:15.280
If you're inside of our markdown, you first, you know, you're going to have to go to the

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:25.200
markdown, you first use this bstheme function and, you know, remind yourself, oh, yeah,

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:26.719
I want to change the base font.

00:13:27.679 --> 00:13:35.039
And if you want to use this with the normal R programming usage, you have to remember,

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:43.200
oh, I want to actually use this font in Google Helper, and then give the family name.

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:48.000
And that's just kind of an indication to tell bslib, hey, this is actually, you know,

00:13:48.559 --> 00:13:54.080
a font that I want you to make sure, like, the font files are actually included with

00:13:54.080 --> 00:14:01.440
the end website and are actually, you know, made available and used for that base font

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:01.840
setting.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:10.400
Because if you were to do it this way, it would just change the CSS style without actually

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:15.919
bringing in any of the actual font files needed to render that font.

00:14:18.799 --> 00:14:26.559
So, yeah, that's an important distinction to remember, that this is the way you would

00:14:26.559 --> 00:14:30.479
want to specify something like this on the R side, like with Shiny.

00:14:32.479 --> 00:14:36.159
But this is the way you specify it in our markdown.

00:14:36.719 --> 00:14:41.919
Let me just go back to, like, a more simple example with Shiny.

00:14:41.919 --> 00:14:47.119
So, this is kind of like the example we saw on the homepage for bslib.

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:58.400
And let's just, you know, create a navbar page with the typical navbar page usage.

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:06.719
So, this is just a simple Shiny app where I have two tabs here, A and B, and I can click

00:15:06.719 --> 00:15:09.520
back and forth to look at page A and page B.

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:13.280
And that's fine.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.039
That works just fine.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:25.840
But let me actually take, show you how I would actually take this theme from our markdown

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:30.640
document and bring that into my Shiny app.

00:15:31.599 --> 00:15:42.559
So, I will take those arguments, try to get multiple cursors here, change these colons

00:15:42.559 --> 00:15:46.239
to equal, make sure I have commas at the end.

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:55.119
Base font, remember, requires a special font Google function.

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:02.799
I'm going to do that for the base font and the heading font.

00:16:02.799 --> 00:16:16.320
And now I should be able to run that and have the same sort of theme look to,

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:19.679
something went wrong here.

00:16:19.679 --> 00:16:20.559
Forgot a comma.

00:16:21.520 --> 00:16:24.320
Wonder how much my life has been wasted on that problem.

00:16:27.039 --> 00:16:30.000
So, yeah, now we got the new different fonts in there.

00:16:30.080 --> 00:16:38.000
And, again, like the nav bar background color is another sort of like mixture between this

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:43.840
darkest black background color that is going to be used for the body and the foreground

00:16:43.840 --> 00:16:45.520
color that's used for the text.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:58.159
So, and these are just warnings that I actually don't have like the best contrast ratio.

00:16:59.119 --> 00:17:06.239
And this is something that this is kind of like a side thing that I think more advanced

00:17:06.239 --> 00:17:11.280
Shiny developers might want to know about that more recently we've added a function

00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:19.040
in Shiny called dev mode where we kind of set at least a handful of different options

00:17:19.040 --> 00:17:23.040
for you that are convenient for developing Shiny applications.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:30.000
So, I actually have this set of my R profile and this is a warning that I will only get

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:36.079
in development mode that, you know, obviously we don't always want to be throwing these

00:17:36.079 --> 00:17:39.119
warnings when you're like running this Shiny app in production.

00:17:40.319 --> 00:17:45.359
So, it's something we just like if we have warnings or other things that we think only

00:17:45.920 --> 00:17:56.719
developers should see, that's something we'll only emit when you have this dev mode set

00:17:56.719 --> 00:17:59.599
and to set it all you need to do is call that function.

00:18:03.119 --> 00:18:03.439
All right.

00:18:03.439 --> 00:18:05.520
But let's do a little bit more here.

00:18:06.079 --> 00:18:15.040
As I mentioned, like this BS theme, we really only have like 10 or 15 different arguments

00:18:15.920 --> 00:18:21.599
documented here, the bootstrap version, a boot swatch theme if you want one, and then

00:18:21.599 --> 00:18:26.239
like the more like main color and font settings.

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:34.560
But if you want to get more targeted with your theming, hopefully we have a link here.

00:18:37.199 --> 00:18:38.079
Not a great link.

00:18:38.079 --> 00:18:44.079
We could probably provide a better link here to this article on the BSLib websites.

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:51.680
You'll find this dropdown has both Bootstrap 5 and Bootstrap 4 SAS variables.

00:18:52.719 --> 00:18:59.199
And this is a big interactive table with hundreds of different theme settings for

00:18:59.199 --> 00:19:04.319
customizing lots of different things that go into Bootstrap.

00:19:05.839 --> 00:19:10.800
Just know like if you're new to Bootstrap, there's a lot more here than you probably

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:19.839
even want to know about because there are like certain components that Bootstrap makes

00:19:19.839 --> 00:19:29.040
available that we at least currently don't make that available, super available to you

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:29.680
in Shiny.

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:37.439
So there are things like, just give you a couple examples, like in Bootstrap itself,

00:19:38.239 --> 00:19:48.239
there are some components like accordions and like alert boxes and carousels,

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:55.280
some different components that we don't like provide like official R wrappers for in Shiny

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:55.920
package.

00:19:55.920 --> 00:20:00.319
But, you know, some extension packages make this stuff available.

00:20:00.319 --> 00:20:05.199
There's like a BS plus package that has wrapped some of these components.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.319
And some other projects out there.

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:17.359
But, you know, you can also use those things more directly by essentially like taking this

00:20:17.359 --> 00:20:22.560
HTML to implement a carousel and writing that in R yourself.

00:20:25.199 --> 00:20:29.839
So if you actually wanted to do something like that, just to quickly show you.

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:41.920
You could basically copy that HTML over and say, I want this div with an ID of this and

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:47.599
a class of this and a data BS right of that.

00:20:51.119 --> 00:20:57.439
So there is an actual R API that like Shiny provides to you to like write that same HTML

00:20:57.439 --> 00:21:00.479
as R code and include that in your Shiny app.

00:21:00.479 --> 00:21:05.599
And lots of people do that, like write custom HTML.

00:21:07.599 --> 00:21:13.839
So like it would be possible to just like write the same HTML and get a carousel.

00:21:13.839 --> 00:21:18.959
But I'm not going to actually go through like a real example of that.

00:21:18.959 --> 00:21:24.959
But just to kind of point out, like there's a whole lot of like stuff that Bootstrap exposes

00:21:24.959 --> 00:21:25.280
to you.

00:21:26.239 --> 00:21:30.400
And that's why there's hundreds of different SAS variables is.

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:39.599
Because if you search this table here for something like an accordion,

00:21:40.400 --> 00:21:45.680
there's settings for like setting the padding on the accordion, like the background color,

00:21:45.680 --> 00:21:53.359
the border width, like pretty much every single little small detail that would make sense to

00:21:53.359 --> 00:21:55.280
have like a high level control for.

00:21:56.640 --> 00:22:02.400
They'll provide it to you through this SAS variable theming interface.

00:22:03.599 --> 00:22:11.439
So not only that, we've actually done some work to like make some common things a bit

00:22:11.439 --> 00:22:14.160
easier for Shiny app developers.

00:22:14.959 --> 00:22:22.079
So one thing in particular is like this nav bar background color is not an actual like

00:22:22.079 --> 00:22:25.760
Bootstrap thing, but we've just added it to make your life easier.

00:22:26.560 --> 00:22:37.760
Where if you wanted to take this basic nav bar page and instead of let me just refresh

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:47.280
our memory here and point out like this kind of 50% gray essentially being used for the

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:48.719
background of this nav bar.

00:22:49.520 --> 00:22:56.800
I could set this nav bar dash BG to purple.

00:22:58.880 --> 00:23:02.560
Now I have a purple background for my nav bar.

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:11.280
And not only that, but BSLib will do some extra work to like make sure that you get

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:13.359
a sensible contrast by default.

00:23:14.079 --> 00:23:23.280
So if you wanted like a light blue instead, notice how on this more darker purple,

00:23:25.359 --> 00:23:29.839
you get a light foreground color to contrast that dark color.

00:23:30.640 --> 00:23:38.400
But now if I do a light color on the nav bar, it's flipped the text color to dark instead

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:44.160
of light.

